      "updated": 1768591836496,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "FRs:\n* Global Alerting & Event Framework\n    - Cool Down w/ Idempotency ( at-least-once )\n    - Alert Metric\n* Analytics Dashboard over long periods of time and multi region \n    - not real time \n    - 3 years retention default\n    - rollups daily(1 day), weekly(1 year), monthly(3 years) \n* Real time dashboards for troubleshooting (default ingestion rate 30s however, tenant can override ) (p50 <50ms, p95< 500ms)\n* Metrics: Push Gateway 5%, Metrics exposure for deployed pods 95% # need both for clients that wish to push metics.\n* Global Monitoring service to monitor the Monitoring Systems\n    - Prometheus Liveliness, Tenant Disk Usage, ingestion rate to thanos, thanos lag, alert rate limit breach, query time, Alerts Dashboard  \n* Tenant Isolation and Management Services w/ RBAC\n    - Policies: \n        Rbac Access: Ad-groups(access to prometheus, grafana, or thanos storage bucket on query)\n        Local Prometheus: (true/false), ingestion rate, rollup policy per namespace(default 1m(2 days)→5m(1 week) max 9 days), alerting rules\n        Local Prometheus footprint: pvc size, memory size, cpu size, redundancy \n        Grafana: Grafana Dashboards Json\n        Push Gateway: (true/false), memory, cpu, redundancy\n        Thanos: whitelist long term metrics, thanos ingestion rate, thanos retention policies, thanos query time budget\n        Event Management: alert rate limit\n* Tenant Chargeback, Autoscaling, and Data Rollup/TTL\n    - Chargeback: Prometheus(Memory, CPU, Disk), thanos ingestion rate, Thanos Storage Bucket\n* Timeseries Database( Prometheus + Thanos)\n    - Prometheus is Active-Active with failover for the ingestion pipeline and query\n    - All data is written locally and then forwarded to prevent bottlenecks\n\nTestable FR set:\nSRE:\n* Overview of Alerting through the Alerts Metric and Alerts Dashboard\n* Local Dashboards w/ Alerts fired\n\nApp Team: \n* Direct configuration of Alerts\n* Direct configuration of Dashboards\n* Direct configuration management of Metrics pipeline for cost management\n* Events System can give them access to send alert via page, email, or slack based on their needs but that lives inside the Events they setup\n* Push Gateway grants users an easy means to forward business logic metrics\n\nPlatform Team:\n* Global Dashboard for monitoring\n* Chargeback for Cost Accountability to users\n* Alerting on Platform Components\n\n\nNFRs:\n* Availability: DP 99.99%(runtime 99.99%, ingestion 99.999%, alerting 99.999%), CP 99.99% (query 99.99%, tenant services 99.99%)\n    Note: SLO applies to admitted requests. Requests rejected due to policy (quota/budget/rate-limit) are not an outage; they’re expected behavior.\n* RPO/RTO:\n        •        Local runtime dashboards: RPO≈0 (Prom WAL), RTO<5m (local)\n        •        Regional durability to object store: RPO≤5m normally; degrades to “bounded by receiver disk” during object-store outage\n        •        Global analytics: RPO≤30m cross-region; RTO≤1h for full-region loss\n* Scale: tenants(1,000+), Clusters(10,000+), active series(10,000,000+), 30/sec scrape interval default, samples/sec(333,333), peak QPS(1,000), peak dashboard concurrency(1,000), 1.5 bytes per sample after\ncompression but we can say 3 bytes per sample for conservative reasoning(index/metadata,storage)\n* multi-region: Local metrics and dashboards have no dependancies and work in partial failures. Alerts can be configured to run at the local level for high priority alerting. In a network partitioning outage or\nThanos Receiver outage global metrics and alerts will be delayed. Regional Storage bucket outages will cause Load Balancers to push data to other regions causing additional cost but no outage.  \n* Security: AuthN+AuthZ, encrypted data at rest, global query audit, secrets stored in Vault\n* Cost: Guardrails for all tenants will have defaults but users can change things based on their needs to drive down cost vs platform tier. This comes with the ability to impact availability. These are the\ncomponents put in place to manage cost: 1/ opt-in adoption and customization sizing for users to tune based on their needs and budget, 2/ ingestions pipeline cost mapping to reduce unused metrics, 3/ data\nretention policies, 4/ global query budget with chargeback\n* Both Prometheus instances are always scrapping and both are forwarding to the Thanos Receiver.* Global Queries: Range 80%, instant 10%, label 10%\n\n\nAPIs:\n    Controlled Answer:\n        I won’t enumerate every endpoint, but the API surface splits into Control Plane spec/status and Data Plane ingest/query/alert, with explicit rollout and audit.\n\n        Auth: Service↔Service uses mTLS (SPIFFE/SVID); User↔Service uses OIDC. Tenant identity is derived by the gateway, not client-supplied.\n\n        Control Plane (async reconciled desired state):\n            •        TenantSpec: create/update tenant; RBAC bindings; quotas/budgets; retention/rollup; enablement/sizing for local Prom/Pushgateway; allowed datasources (local vs global).\n            •        Artifacts: register dashboard JSON + alert rule bundles (stored + versioned; GitHub as source where applicable).\n            •        Rollouts: create rollout of a versioned config bundle; canary/promote; pause; rollback.\n            •        TenantStatus: per-region/per-cluster convergence status, last-applied version, drift flags, and rollout history.\n            •        Usage/Billing: read current usage vs budgets for ingest/query/storage (for chargeback and guardrails).\n            •        Audit: query/config change audit retrieval (tenant + time range).\n\n        Data Plane:\n            •        Ingestion: scrape /metrics; Pushgateway write path; remote_write to Receiver with tenant identity enforced and per-tenant rate limits (429 with limit reason + retry guidance).\n            •        Query: PromQL-compatible local endpoint for troubleshooting and global endpoint for long-range; query budgets enforced; responses include limit-hit details.\n            •        Alerting: tenant rule management + evaluation (Thanos Ruler or local Prom rules), Alertmanager routing, idempotency/cooldowns, silences, and alert state/history retrieval.\n\n  Deep Dive:\n    Control Plane: \n            Tenant: Real Answer: an async control plane API for tenant configuration and policy\n                Tenant\n                RBAC binding per AD-Group\n                tenant mapping \n                per-tenant-global limits\n                LB / gateway authn/authz\n                rate limiting\n                audit export\n                downsample rules\n                rollback\n                runtime management(sizing, redundancy, on/off)(push gateway, prometheus, grafana)\n                runtime dashboards and alerts are stored in GitHub as an authoritative registry and uploaded to image repositories per Tenant ID\n            Global Query: \n                PromQL Global Thanos Endpoints, \n                Global Grafana Dashboard endpoint, \n                API Gateway authn/authz, \n                global queries can use cluster_id and tenant_id to define unique metrics to their system globally, \n                budget enforcement/management, \n                global dashboards and alerts are stored in GitHub as an authoritative registry per Tenant ID triggering real time build, test, and deployment \n            Global Alerts: \n                Thanos alert rules always fire to an AlertManager\n                AlertManager will have 4 patterns page, email, slack, and webhook\n                Alerts fired will be also stored as a metric for monitoring\n                Alert configuration is based on Thanos Alerting Rules with cooldown and idempotent id = tenant_id, alert_id\n                AlertManager Manages group rate limiting by group, alert, or alert type\n    Data Plane:\n        Ingestion: \n            remote_write endpoints behind LB /gateway, authn/authz, tenant headers, rate limits, pod metrics exporters and prometheus discover, push gateway behind LB /gateway + auth push to local\nprometheus, Prometheus Remote write -> Thanos Receiver add Label cluster_id and tenant_id to all forwarded metrics\n        Local Query: Namespace Prometheus/Grafana endpoint behind API Gateway with Authn/Authz\n    \n\n \nData:   \n Tenant Database(RDBMS Authoritative): Note: Insert/Update/Delete triggers on every table forward to topic for the controller to audit and begin updating\n        Tenant: Key(pk serial int tenant_id) Value(roles[ad_groups], budgets, usage, role_up_rules, retention, storage_bucket_url, version)\n            Child entities (namespace, cluster, policy bundles, images, quotas, budgets, rollup/retention).\n         Note: Every Entity has a version, timestamp, and user_id for audit reasons\n         Note: Prometheus owns all namespace metics(sample, metadata, index, block) for the runtime env on PVC\n                Thanos owns all metrics forwarded by Tenant and stored in an individual Tenant Object storage(sample, metadata, index, block)\n Redis Cache:\n        key(tenant_id) value(budgets, budgets used, roles{admin[ad_groups], write[ad_groups], read[ad_groups]})\n\n Audit log schema (query + config changes): Cassandra partitioned by tenant + day for both query and config, move to object storage after 90 days, multi region write service\n Object storage blocks per cluster/region prefixing | individual storage bucket per tenant for metrics\n GitHub: Dashboards + Alerts: github\n        Dashboards:\n            structure global: {tenant_id}/dashboard/global/{file_name}.json, Runtime: {tenant_id}/dashboard/runtime/{file_name}.json\n        Alerts:\n            structure Global: {tenant_id}/alert/global/{file_name}.yaml, Runtime: {tenant_id}/alert/runtime/{file_name}.yaml\n        Prometheus and Grafana images stored in image repository versioned for all global users with history of build stored in the repo along with the user_id and timestamp\n  Object Storage for chargeback: hourly tenant_id, (\n        runtime rates: daemon processes on each kubernetes cluster fetching from namespace prometheus metrics every 5 minutes stored in bronze bucket\n        ingestion rates: querying thanos for egress, cpu, PVC, and memory\n        metrics object store: Fetch cost per object store from cloud provider )\n        Note: These three metrics will be fetched through a Batch Spark Job after the SLA of persistence is met. They will be consolidated into a silver bucket for each tenant_id.\n\nNotes: Object Storage and the RDBMS are replicated to another region. Budgets used in cache is by hour and can be replayed from thanos and everything else in the cache has SOT in the RDBMS. Cassandra\nwill use a Cassandra service to write twice and a read LB to find the closest Geo Cassandra instance. No writes will be allowed to the cassandra instance without going through the service.  ",
      "fontSize": 20.484621692999625,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "FRs:\n* Global Alerting & Event Framework\n    - Cool Down w/ Idempotency ( at-least-once )\n    - Alert Metric\n* Analytics Dashboard over long periods of time and multi region \n    - not real time \n    - 3 years retention default\n    - rollups daily(1 day), weekly(1 year), monthly(3 years) \n* Real time dashboards for troubleshooting (default ingestion rate 30s however, tenant can override ) (p50 <50ms, p95< 500ms)\n* Metrics: Push Gateway 5%, Metrics exposure for deployed pods 95% # need both for clients that wish to push metics.\n* Global Monitoring service to monitor the Monitoring Systems\n    - Prometheus Liveliness, Tenant Disk Usage, ingestion rate to thanos, thanos lag, alert rate limit breach, query time, Alerts Dashboard  \n* Tenant Isolation and Management Services w/ RBAC\n    - Policies: \n        Rbac Access: Ad-groups(access to prometheus, grafana, or thanos storage bucket on query)\n        Local Prometheus: (true/false), ingestion rate, rollup policy per namespace(default 1m(2 days)→5m(1 week) max 9 days), alerting rules\n        Local Prometheus footprint: pvc size, memory size, cpu size, redundancy \n        Grafana: Grafana Dashboards Json\n        Push Gateway: (true/false), memory, cpu, redundancy\n        Thanos: whitelist long term metrics, thanos ingestion rate, thanos retention policies, thanos query time budget\n        Event Management: alert rate limit\n* Tenant Chargeback, Autoscaling, and Data Rollup/TTL\n    - Chargeback: Prometheus(Memory, CPU, Disk), thanos ingestion rate, Thanos Storage Bucket\n* Timeseries Database( Prometheus + Thanos)\n    - Prometheus is Active-Active with failover for the ingestion pipeline and query\n    - All data is written locally and then forwarded to prevent bottlenecks\n\nTestable FR set:\nSRE:\n* Overview of Alerting through the Alerts Metric and Alerts Dashboard\n* Local Dashboards w/ Alerts fired\n\nApp Team: \n* Direct configuration of Alerts\n* Direct configuration of Dashboards\n* Direct configuration management of Metrics pipeline for cost management\n* Events System can give them access to send alert via page, email, or slack based on their needs but that lives inside the Events they setup\n* Push Gateway grants users an easy means to forward business logic metrics\n\nPlatform Team:\n* Global Dashboard for monitoring\n* Chargeback for Cost Accountability to users\n* Alerting on Platform Components\n\n\nNFRs:\n* Availability: DP 99.99%(runtime 99.99%, ingestion 99.999%, alerting 99.999%), CP 99.99% (query 99.99%, tenant services 99.99%)\n    Note: SLO applies to admitted requests. Requests rejected due to policy (quota/budget/rate-limit) are not an outage; they’re expected behavior.\n* RPO/RTO:\n        •        Local runtime dashboards: RPO≈0 (Prom WAL), RTO<5m (local)\n        •        Regional durability to object store: RPO≤5m normally; degrades to “bounded by receiver disk” during object-store outage\n        •        Global analytics: RPO≤30m cross-region; RTO≤1h for full-region loss\n* Scale: tenants(1,000+), Clusters(10,000+), active series(10,000,000+), 30/sec scrape interval default, samples/sec(333,333), peak QPS(1,000), peak dashboard concurrency(1,000), 1.5 bytes per sample after compression but we can say 3 bytes per sample for conservative reasoning(index/metadata,storage)\n* multi-region: Local metrics and dashboards have no dependancies and work in partial failures. Alerts can be configured to run at the local level for high priority alerting. In a network partitioning outage or Thanos Receiver outage global metrics and alerts will be delayed. Regional Storage bucket outages will cause Load Balancers to push data to other regions causing additional cost but no outage.  \n* Security: AuthN+AuthZ, encrypted data at rest, global query audit, secrets stored in Vault\n* Cost: Guardrails for all tenants will have defaults but users can change things based on their needs to drive down cost vs platform tier. This comes with the ability to impact availability. These are the components put in place to manage cost: 1/ opt-in adoption and customization sizing for users to tune based on their needs and budget, 2/ ingestions pipeline cost mapping to reduce unused metrics, 3/ data retention policies, 4/ global query budget with chargeback\n* Both Prometheus instances are always scrapping and both are forwarding to the Thanos Receiver.* Global Queries: Range 80%, instant 10%, label 10%\n\n\nAPIs:\n    Controlled Answer:\n        I won’t enumerate every endpoint, but the API surface splits into Control Plane spec/status and Data Plane ingest/query/alert, with explicit rollout and audit.\n\n        Auth: Service↔Service uses mTLS (SPIFFE/SVID); User↔Service uses OIDC. Tenant identity is derived by the gateway, not client-supplied.\n\n        Control Plane (async reconciled desired state):\n            •        TenantSpec: create/update tenant; RBAC bindings; quotas/budgets; retention/rollup; enablement/sizing for local Prom/Pushgateway; allowed datasources (local vs global).\n            •        Artifacts: register dashboard JSON + alert rule bundles (stored + versioned; GitHub as source where applicable).\n            •        Rollouts: create rollout of a versioned config bundle; canary/promote; pause; rollback.\n            •        TenantStatus: per-region/per-cluster convergence status, last-applied version, drift flags, and rollout history.\n            •        Usage/Billing: read current usage vs budgets for ingest/query/storage (for chargeback and guardrails).\n            •        Audit: query/config change audit retrieval (tenant + time range).\n\n        Data Plane:\n            •        Ingestion: scrape /metrics; Pushgateway write path; remote_write to Receiver with tenant identity enforced and per-tenant rate limits (429 with limit reason + retry guidance).\n            •        Query: PromQL-compatible local endpoint for troubleshooting and global endpoint for long-range; query budgets enforced; responses include limit-hit details.\n            •        Alerting: tenant rule management + evaluation (Thanos Ruler or local Prom rules), Alertmanager routing, idempotency/cooldowns, silences, and alert state/history retrieval.\n\n  Deep Dive:\n    Control Plane: \n            Tenant: Real Answer: an async control plane API for tenant configuration and policy\n                Tenant\n                RBAC binding per AD-Group\n                tenant mapping \n                per-tenant-global limits\n                LB / gateway authn/authz\n                rate limiting\n                audit export\n                downsample rules\n                rollback\n                runtime management(sizing, redundancy, on/off)(push gateway, prometheus, grafana)\n                runtime dashboards and alerts are stored in GitHub as an authoritative registry and uploaded to image repositories per Tenant ID\n            Global Query: \n                PromQL Global Thanos Endpoints, \n                Global Grafana Dashboard endpoint, \n                API Gateway authn/authz, \n                global queries can use cluster_id and tenant_id to define unique metrics to their system globally, \n                budget enforcement/management, \n                global dashboards and alerts are stored in GitHub as an authoritative registry per Tenant ID triggering real time build, test, and deployment \n            Global Alerts: \n                Thanos alert rules always fire to an AlertManager\n                AlertManager will have 4 patterns page, email, slack, and webhook\n                Alerts fired will be also stored as a metric for monitoring\n                Alert configuration is based on Thanos Alerting Rules with cooldown and idempotent id = tenant_id, alert_id\n                AlertManager Manages group rate limiting by group, alert, or alert type\n    Data Plane:\n        Ingestion: \n            remote_write endpoints behind LB /gateway, authn/authz, tenant headers, rate limits, pod metrics exporters and prometheus discover, push gateway behind LB /gateway + auth push to local prometheus, Prometheus Remote write -> Thanos Receiver add Label cluster_id and tenant_id to all forwarded metrics\n        Local Query: Namespace Prometheus/Grafana endpoint behind API Gateway with Authn/Authz\n    \n\n \nData:   \n Tenant Database(RDBMS Authoritative): Note: Insert/Update/Delete triggers on every table forward to topic for the controller to audit and begin updating\n        Tenant: Key(pk serial int tenant_id) Value(roles[ad_groups], budgets, usage, role_up_rules, retention, storage_bucket_url, version)\n            Child entities (namespace, cluster, policy bundles, images, quotas, budgets, rollup/retention).\n         Note: Every Entity has a version, timestamp, and user_id for audit reasons\n         Note: Prometheus owns all namespace metics(sample, metadata, index, block) for the runtime env on PVC\n                Thanos owns all metrics forwarded by Tenant and stored in an individual Tenant Object storage(sample, metadata, index, block)\n Redis Cache:\n        key(tenant_id) value(budgets, budgets used, roles{admin[ad_groups], write[ad_groups], read[ad_groups]})\n\n Audit log schema (query + config changes): Cassandra partitioned by tenant + day for both query and config, move to object storage after 90 days, multi region write service\n Object storage blocks per cluster/region prefixing | individual storage bucket per tenant for metrics\n GitHub: Dashboards + Alerts: github\n        Dashboards:\n            structure global: {tenant_id}/dashboard/global/{file_name}.json, Runtime: {tenant_id}/dashboard/runtime/{file_name}.json\n        Alerts:\n            structure Global: {tenant_id}/alert/global/{file_name}.yaml, Runtime: {tenant_id}/alert/runtime/{file_name}.yaml\n        Prometheus and Grafana images stored in image repository versioned for all global users with history of build stored in the repo along with the user_id and timestamp\n  Object Storage for chargeback: hourly tenant_id, (\n        runtime rates: daemon processes on each kubernetes cluster fetching from namespace prometheus metrics every 5 minutes stored in bronze bucket\n        ingestion rates: querying thanos for egress, cpu, PVC, and memory\n        metrics object store: Fetch cost per object store from cloud provider )\n        Note: These three metrics will be fetched through a Batch Spark Job after the SLA of persistence is met. They will be consolidated into a silver bucket for each tenant_id.\n\nNotes: Object Storage and the RDBMS are replicated to another region. Budgets used in cache is by hour and can be replayed from thanos and everything else in the cache has SOT in the RDBMS. Cassandra will use a Cassandra service to write twice and a read LB to find the closest Geo Cassandra instance. No writes will be allowed to the cassandra instance without going through the service.  ",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "ixwiYIDKN9AfN4N-UO5Xm",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1488.7737107491998,
      "y": -396.3363605887546,
      "width": 1185.0859374999998,
      "height": 350,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
