    },
    {
      "id": "Dp7F8tVjYzFGnilaRU4cD",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1015.953707553306,
      "y": 4396.600283136794,
      "width": 1959.0715274026334,
      "height": 250,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3d",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1058890808,
      "version": 1931,
      "versionNonce": 795142984,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1768229063810,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\nTop 3 bottle necks \n   * Users can break local prometheus if the data has high volumes, cardinality, too many remote forwarded metrics, or retention is too long. To prevent this we will over provision initially but Tenant\nowners need to understand and be accountable for Availability of prometheus and driving down the reduction of resources.\n   * Alertmanager is a single point of failure. We will have many instances across many regions but mapping to individual local instances per region can cause availability issues. We will failover to another\nlocal instance in the region if a major outage occurs but this could cause duplicate alerts when failing over. \n   * Tenant isolation and management for Thanos in general is not the most advanced. Other services like Mimir can help drive tenant isolation but they have 1/4 the adoption and the license is not\nApache. Also they still cannot provide all the tenant isolation features we would like such as budget boundaries outside of internal budgets on a query. Blocking query execution in general is not a\nnormal practice. We can block query execution by users through a Traefik and a KV store but it is more manual than I would like and this should still not block alerting rules as those impact real\noperations. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\nTop 3 bottle necks \n   * Users can break local prometheus if the data has high volumes, cardinality, too many remote forwarded metrics, or retention is too long. To prevent this we will over provision initially but Tenant owners need to understand and be accountable for Availability of prometheus and driving down the reduction of resources.\n   * Alertmanager is a single point of failure. We will have many instances across many regions but mapping to individual local instances per region can cause availability issues. We will failover to another local instance in the region if a major outage occurs but this could cause duplicate alerts when failing over. \n   * Tenant isolation and management for Thanos in general is not the most advanced. Other services like Mimir can help drive tenant isolation but they have 1/4 the adoption and the license is not Apache. Also they still cannot provide all the tenant isolation features we would like such as budget boundaries outside of internal budgets on a query. Blocking query execution in general is not a normal practice. We can block query execution by users through a Traefik and a KV store but it is more manual than I would like and this should still not block alerting rules as those impact real operations. ",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
